Perlman was born in 1945 in Tel Aviv.
Perlman contracted polio at age four and has walked using leg braces and crutches since then and plays the violin while seated.
At the age of three, he was denied admission to the Shulamit Conservatory for being too small to hold a violin.

He instead taught himself how to play the instrument using a toy fiddle until he was old enough to study with Rivka Goldgart at the Shulamit Conservatory and at the Academy of Music in Tel Aviv (now the Buchmann-Mehta School of Music), where he gave his first recital at age 10.
He moved to the U.S. at age 13 to study at the Juilliard School with the violin teacher Ivan Galamian and his assistant Dorothy DeLay.
